**Calculation 2** provides us with important details about the relationships between lengths and angles linked to location on a circle, as described below:
- **Line 1**: Informs us that the square of the horizontal projection of the radius **a** (c&sup2; cos &sup2; (θ)), added to the square of its vertical projection **b** (c&sup2; sin &sup2; (θ)) is equal to the square of the total length of the radius (c&sup2;), also known as the **hypotenuse**;
- **Line 2**: Since the sum of the squares of the projections of the radius is equal to the square of the radius itself, we express the partial quantities in relation to the total in the denominator;
- **Line 3**: Since both projections have the radius c in common, we factor out this value, separating it from the parts that depend on the angle;
- **Line 4**: By isolating the whole from its components, we obtain the unit value (c&sup2; / c&sup2;), which we have as a single quantity again (1).
- **Line 5**: As a consequence, it becomes explicit that the sum of the cosine squared of θ and the sine squared of θ is equal to 1.

#### The location on the circle

Given this information, we can rewrite **Formula 1** in different ways, all representing our exact position on a circle at point **P** (**Graph 4**):

From **Formula 4**, we conclude that we can describe our position on a circle in the following ways:
- **Line 1**: Point **P** is at a distance **x** from the origin **O** and at a distance **y** from that same origin **O**.
- **Line 2**: The distance **x** corresponds to the length of leg **a**, which projects the hypotenuse **c** onto the horizontal, while the distance **y** corresponds to the length of leg **b**, which projects the hypotenuse **c** onto the vertical;
- **Line 3**: The total length of the projections can be expressed using the radius **c**, which represents the distance from the origin, and the angle θ, which represents the opening of the radius from the horizontal in a counterclockwise direction. Thus, we have the horizontal path expressed as <b>x = a = c × cos (θ)</b>, while the path made vertically can be expressed as <b>y = b = c × sin (θ)</b>.

